  "prompt": "How do I prove that ((sinA) ^2) +1/ (sinA) ^2) ((cosA) ^2) +1/ (cosA) ^2)) \u226525/4?",
  "response": "To prove the inequality \n\n\\[\n\\frac{(\\sin A)^2 + 1}{(\\sin A)^2} + \\frac{(\\cos A)^2 + 1}{(\\cos A)^2} \\geq \\frac{25}{4},\n\\]\n\nlet's start by rewriting the terms involved.\n\nDefine \\( x = (\\sin A)^2 \\) and \\( y = (\\cos A)^2 \\). We know from the Pythagorean identity that:\n\n\\[\nx + y = 1.\n\\]\n\nNow, we can rewrite the left-hand side of the inequality:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{x + 1}{x} + \\frac{y + 1}{y} = \\left( \\frac{x}{x} + \\frac{1}{x} \\right) + \\left( \\frac{y}{y} + \\frac{1}{y} \\right) = 2 + \\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y}.\n\\]\n\nThus, we need to show:\n\n\\[\n2 + \\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y} \\geq \\frac{25}{4}.\n\\]\n\nThis rearranges to:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y} \\geq \\frac{25}{4} - 2,\n\\]\nwhich simplifies to:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y} \\geq \\frac{25}{4} - \\frac{8}{4} = \\frac{17}{4}.\n\\]\n\nUsing the identity \\( x + y = 1 \\), we can express \\( \\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y} \\) in a different way:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y} = \\frac{y + x}{xy} = \\frac{1}{xy}.\n\\]\n\nHence, we need to prove:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{xy} \\geq \\frac{17}{4}.\n\\]\n\nThis can be rearranged to:\n\n\\[\nxy \\leq \\frac{4}{17}.\n\\]\n\nNow, we can use the AM-GM inequality:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{x + y}{2} \\geq \\sqrt{xy} \\implies \\frac{1}{2} \\geq \\sqrt{xy} \\implies \\frac{1}{4} \\geq xy.\n\\]\n\nNow we need to check whether \\( \\frac{4}{17} \\leq \\frac{1}{4} \\):\n\nCross-multiplying gives:\n\n\\[\n4 \\cdot 4 \\leq 17 \\implies 16 \\leq 17,\n\\]\n\nwhich is true. Therefore, \\( xy \\leq \\frac{4}{17} \\) holds, confirming that \n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{xy} \\geq \\frac{17}{4},\n\\]\n\nand consequently, \n\n\\[\n\\frac{(\\sin A)^2 + 1}{(\\sin A)^2} + \\frac{(\\cos A)^2 + 1}{(\\cos A)^2} \\geq \\frac{25}{4}.\n\\]\n\nThus, we have proven the original inequality. \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{ \\frac{(\\sin A)^2 + 1}{(\\sin A)^2} + \\frac{(\\cos A)^2 + 1}{(\\cos A)^2} \\geq \\frac{25}{4}. }\n\\]",
